docs.lead_paragraph: President Biden has called for the release of Evan Gershkovich, an American Wall Street Journal reporter imprisoned in Russia, praising his courage and saying the United States was working tirelessly to bring him home.

headline.main: Biden Praises ‘Absolute Courage’ of U.S. Journalist Detained in Russia

docs.abstract: Randi Schofield is the sole provider for an ailing father and, at the same time, for her own children — a situation now common among Americans in their 30s and 40s.
docs.snippet: Randi Schofield is the sole provider for an ailing father and, at the same time, for her own children — a situation now common among Americans in their 30s and 40s.
docs.lead_paragraph: In January 2022, Randi Schofield was a 34-year-old single mother who, not long before, left her full-time job of eight years as a personal bailiff to a local judge. She pulled $30,000 from her retirement savings and was planning to give herself all of 2022 to expand the small catering business she had always dreamed about. This would be the year she bet on herself. Then, that month, she received the news that medics were pulling her father out of his car.

headline.main: The Sunday Read: ‘The Agony of Putting Your Life on Hold to Care for Your Parents’

docs.abstract: If the Writers Guild does decide to go on strike, it won’t be about money, it will be about survival.
docs.snippet: If the Writers Guild does decide to go on strike, it won’t be about money, it will be about survival.
docs.lead_paragraph: An old Klingon proverb tells us, “Only a fool fights in a burning house.” In light of that bit of wisdom from “Star Trek,” it might seem surprising that the Writers Guild of America West and East, the sister unions that represent the country’s film and television writers, are engaged in a fraught labor negotiation with the studios and streaming companies that could lead, after their contract expires on May 1, to Hollywood’s biggest strike in 15 years.

headline.main: The Hollywood Writers’ Strike Isn’t About Money, It’s About Survival

docs.lead_paragraph: The four of us spent the last three years immersed in collecting and reporting data on Covid-19 from every corner of the world, building one of the most trusted sources of information on cases and deaths available anywhere. But we stopped in March, not because the pandemic is over (it isn’t), but because much of the vital public health information we need is no longer available.

docs.snippet: Officials had not yet been able to identify the gas or the source of the leak in the city of Ludhiana, in Punjab State.
docs.lead_paragraph: At least 11 people were killed and almost as many injured after a gas leaked in the northern Indian state of Punjab on Sunday. Officials had sealed off a section of in the city of Ludhiana and were evacuating residents as they tried to identify the gas and determine the source of the leak.

headline.main: Mystery Gas Leak in India Leaves at Least 11 Dead

docs.abstract: Images of the new king may be blanketing Britain, but many in the country are more focused on navigating a cost-of-living crisis than celebrating a dysfunctional royal family.
docs.snippet: Images of the new king may be blanketing Britain, but many in the country are more focused on navigating a cost-of-living crisis than celebrating a dysfunctional royal family.
docs.lead_paragraph: When King Charles III is crowned on Saturday, he will undergo a ritual so rare in modern British history that it last occurred 70 years ago, roughly the wait between sightings of Halley’s comet. And yet the coronation has yet to capture the imagination of a Britain preoccupied by other concerns.

headline.main: Many in U.K. Greet King Charles’s Coronation With a ‘Take It or Leave It’ Shrug

docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Last year, with pandemic lockdowns in the rearview mirror, Whole Foods Market made a bet on a gritty San Francisco neighborhood. The high-end supermarket chain opened a giant flagship store in a part of the city that is home to both tech companies like Twitter and open-air drug dealing.

headline.main: In San Francisco, a Troubled Year at a Whole Foods Market Reflects a City’s Woes
